##Panic, anxiety, despair... you need psychological protection from an epidemic

Micro-signal, Rancaijing

A feature presentation, a daily in depth report, redefines the innovation economy.

Original by ran CAIJING

By Kong Mingming

Editor | Zhou Changfan

In the fight against COVID-19 pneumonia, the invisible enemy is not only the invisible virus, but also the trauma and crisis of the human heart.

Working day and night, panicking at a diagnosis, being isolated and unable to leave the house, being bombarded with information and trapped in a constant state of anxiety and insomnia.., front line medical staff, patients diagnosed and quarantined, the general population on high alert, they are likely to fall into a psychological crisis.

At the national level, psychological crisis intervention has been initiated in response to the outbreak. On January 27, the Disease Control Bureau of the COVID-19 issued the guiding principles for emergency psychological crisis intervention in the case of pneumonia, requiring that psychological crisis intervention be incorporated into the overall plan for epidemic prevention and control. The Wuhan Mental Health Center and the Hubei Psychological Counseling Association have both launched special epidemic psychological assistance hotlines.

Society and business are also moving. Beijing Normal University, Peking University and other universities have opened psychological support hotlines in response to the outbreak, and many social voluntary psychological support groups have also started to provide free psychological services. Internet companies such as JD.com, Weibo, one mind and simple mind have also launched dedicated outbreak psychology services.

Joshua, a beijing-based psychological consultant who has actively participated in the social voluntary psychological assistance team, told Cairen that the epidemic is significant and is a test not only for front-line workers, but also a disaster for the whole society, it can lead to huge psychological trauma in the whole society at the same time, and it can last for quite a long time.

In this case, the psychosocial trauma of the situation will be a long battle that will take more time to address.

Psychological crisis under epidemic situation

Dr. Li, who works in a health clinic in Xiaogan, Hubei Province, is about to collapse.

Dr. Li has been in a state of anxiety since Dec. 21, when he was told to give special treatment to patients with fevers. In the past week he has been exposed to a large number of patients returning home from Wuhan, where doctors are protected only by face masks and other supplies are in short supply. The constant noise of outside information, coupled with worries about the future, Dr. Lee can not sleep every day, "see no future. ".

Some displaced people in Wuhan said that they had recently encountered a series of events, such as being refused a flight by an airline, being refused a room at a bed-and-breakfast, and being unable to return to their homes. They were also worried about their family back home. All he had in his mind was constant anger, exhaustion and tension, often a person secretly cry, also do not see where the future is, often feel desperate.

Lin, who works as a media reporter in Beijing, did not go to the front line, but for the sake of her work, she also needs to keep track of the epidemic information and sort it out. Although she was reassured by some of the aid developments, she was careful to stock up on supplies and stay at home. She kept losing sleep at night, and at one point she was on the verge of a breakdown.

Zhu Lin, a volunteer in psychological counseling, told CNBC that she had been contacted and found that many people were in a state of anxiety and panic. Because can not go out at home, only through the network access to outside information, a lot of information bombing, especially mixed with a lot of rumors and slander, many people in a long-term mental strain. Health care workers are on the front lines of the fight against the epidemic, with heavy workloads and long hours, and emotions deliberately suppressed, with nowhere to vent.

Zhu Lin has been a full time therapist for more than six years. On the afternoon of January 24, after hearing more and more news about the outbreak, she and her friends set up a psychological support team. There are now more than 600 domestic volunteers and 40 overseas volunteers online 24 hours a day, to provide free long-distance psychological counseling service for front-line medical staff and their families, confirmed and suspected patients and their families in Wuhan. "from the very beginning, I wanted to do my part online with a group of like-minded people to help ease the psychological pressure. " As more and more people joined and the influence grew, Zhu Lin was moved, it also kicked off a few days of overwork with only three or four hours of sleep.

Joshua also said that in the cases he's been exposed to so far, most of the people asking for help have come from front-line workers at large hospitals, who are overworked, under constant physical and psychological stress, experiencing emotional disturbances and even hallucinations. There are also people who are affected by their emotions because they see too much hopelessness and helplessness from others, and there are also people who have some degree of hopelessness or even suicidal thoughts.

Physical exhaustion, lack of supplies, emotional spread, many people do not even have time to eat. Coupled with the disaster in the face of the patient's overall panic distress, tension between patients and doctors, so that the entire hospital atmosphere tends to extreme. For psychological help seekers, these conditions create a "doomsday-like feeling. ".

"excessive panic can cause a person to lose control of their own mind and create sub-emotions other than panic, which can trigger a lot of negative emotions that can have a negative effect on the resistance to the epidemic, " Joshua said.

In an epidemic, the spread of the virus is accompanied by the spread of negative emotional and psychological problems, and without professional assistance and rescue, the psychological trauma of the group concerned may be permanent.

Psycho's on the move

Among Zhu Lin's team of volunteers, more than 100 counselors in Wuhan were divided into 10 groups by region, and more than 60 counselors outside Wuhan in Hubei Province were divided into 8 groups by region. More than 450 counsellors in Beijing, Shanghai, Guangdong, Chongqing and other provinces and cities were divided into dozens of groups by region, and more than 40 members of the overseas group were divided into two groups. New People are still coming in.

Volunteer Zhang Yu is a second-level psychological counseling certificate holders. During the outbreak, she worried and worried, hoping to help Hubei do something. On January 26, after the introduction of a friend, she was drawn into the "Hubei Psychological Consultant Association Official Working Group" Wechat Group, and from January 27 began to receive counseling tasks.

In the WECHAT group she joins, the working group arranges the duty groups and the duty hours, there are 24-hour hotline operators, and there are consultation demand dispatchers from 9 am to 9 pm, the team counsellors are on call during the team's duty hours. One volunteer said: "On this day, I talked to 48 strangers, set up eight working groups, entered 24 groups, issued a dozen circulars and documents, drank three glasses of water and walked about 100 steps, but [ compared to fighting the epidemic ] what is this? "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The assisted person expresses thanks to the volunteer of the psychological consultation

Source / interviewee

Cheng Xin, a psychological consultant, told Caijing that the psychological assistance for such urgent and important events is also a test for the consultant himself. At the same time, some counsellors may be overwhelmed by the negative emotions of the counsellors, which requires the counsellors to self-evaluate and judge before accepting the job, otherwise the counsellors will also have psychological trauma.

"But I am willing to do my part, because there are people who need our help, especially in the face of this kind of natural disaster, so long as everyone offers a little help, it may bring about a good chain reaction, " Cheng said.

Despite the fact that one party has needs and the other party is willing to help, Zhu Lin told Caixin that their initial psychological work did not go well. "The problem is that people are anxious, they can't find us, our team is anxious, they can't reach more people, and even if they did, most people don't understand what counseling is for, especially when we reach out to them, and they say no, probably because they don't trust us. " They sent teams of volunteers to reach out to local communities and help more people.

In order to cope with the needs of psychological assistance in epidemic areas, Internet enterprises such as simple psychology, one psychology and other professional psychological service platforms have been working overtime continuously in the past few days, and launched specialized mutual psychological assistance hotlines and services. Jd.com, micro-blog and other enterprises have also set up a special outbreak of psychological services channel.

Joshua, who has 12 years of experience in counseling and counseling, says many people run away or fight to the extreme in the face of major disasters. But in the process, if the public's emotions are properly understood and guided, "instead, these events can be a blessing in their lives, allowing people to learn and grow through their experiences, and even improve their lives significantly. "

On 27 January, a psychological crisis intervention mechanism was also activated at the national level, with the entry of the regular army. The COVID-19 has issued guidelines for emergency psychological crisis intervention in cases of pneumonia, which call for the integration of psychological crisis intervention into the overall plan for epidemic prevention and control. Wuhan Mental Health Center, Hubei Psychological Counseling Association, Beijing Normal University, Peking University and others have also launched a dedicated psychological assistance hotline.

The long battle that had just begun

The battle for psychological support has only just begun.

"according to the current assessment of experts, the outbreak of a large-scale before mid-february, after which the real psychological help will take nearly months to six months, or even longer to help them slowly return to normal, to start to have love, hope and confidence to face the current life, " he said, sALINNA, a psychotherapist with 2,000 hours of personal counseling experience and certified in emergency counseling who also participated in the program, said, "Not only Wuhan and Hubei, but the whole country is experiencing some degree of psychological trauma, including trust in the government, trust between regions, trust between people, " he said.

For the general public, Zhu Lin suggests "less information input, " "better sleep schedules, " and "more entertainment. " She wants people to show encouragement and support when communicating with others, if you really can not handle the emotion, timely seek professional help.

For stressed out, tired front line workers, Zhu Lin recommends a combination of work and rest. Be Sure to set aside time to talk to others about things other than work, such as taking a tenth of your time off to simply talk to a counselor, for anxiety. If you still can not face the death of the patient, constantly fear of depression, to timely seek professional psychological intervention.

Joshua also notes that in the current climate, it's best for the general public to give positive words of encouragement and praise to friends and family. He thinks, insomnia angst is the basic reaction of the body, can try to eat a few basic help sleep medicaments to solve insomnia. You can keep the basic indoor exercise, do more to make themselves quiet things, such as reading, listening to music, eat a reasonable diet, to ensure adequate intake of vegetables and fruits.

SALINNA suggests controlling how much time you spend in your home, giving quality time to close friends, setting realistic milestones, and seeking professional help when necessary. She also suggests trying to manage your negative emotions and inspire positive emotions that are good for you, such as joy, confidence, hope, courage and love.

Joshua said that under the current situation, people in Hubei and even across the country need to pay real attention to the psychological problems, and use the strength of society and the state to help the front-line groups of doctors, patients and patients'families, and the people in the hard-hit areas, but also need a three-dimensional, authoritative, systematic treatment and counseling program, so that these people can quickly come out of the psychological shadow.

Zhu Lin observes that, from the perspective of public reaction and demand in this crisis, when faced with an emergency, the public will experience panic and anxiety, and many people have a physical response, the need for professional psychological assistance to relieve anxiety will become a normal state. She suggested that cities should establish a more professional crisis intervention team and hoped that the government would integrate crisis intervention and psychological assistance into the daily work of the public.

(end of text)

Additional: Psychological Symptom collection and professional psychological assistance information (collated by a psychological assistance public welfare event sponsored by Wemedia, Micromedia Holdings) 

Symptoms of needing to call a psychological helpline

If you have any of the following symptoms or feel that you need to talk about them, you can call the psychological hotline for help.

The following symptoms are collated from the CDC's January 27 update.

1. Confirmed cases

(1) initial stage of isolation treatment

Mindset: Numbness, denial, anger, fear, anxiety, depression, disappointment, complaining, insomnia or aggression.

(2) isolation for treatment

State of mind: in addition to the above-mentioned possible state of mind, there may be loneliness, or fear of disease and do not cooperate, give up treatment, or treatment of excessive optimism and high expectations.

(3) patients suffering from respiratory distress, extreme anxiety and difficulty in expression

State of mind: near death, panic, despair, etc.

(4) patients with mild illness who are isolated at home and those with fever who seek medical treatment in hospitals

STATE OF MIND: Panic, Insecurity, Loneliness, helplessness, depression, pessimism, anger, tension, the pressure of being shunned by others, grievance, shame or neglect of disease, etc. .

Suspected patient

State of mind: Luck Psychology, avoid treatment, fear of being discriminated against, or anxiety, excessive treatment, frequent transfer, etc. .

Health care and related personnel

State of mind: excessive fatigue and tension, even exhaustion, anxiety, insomnia, depression, Sadness, grievance, helplessness, depression, face the death of patients frustrated or self-blame. Fear of infection, fear of family, fear of family fear of themselves. Hyperactive, refusing proper rest, failing to maintain good health, etc. .

Close contacts (family members, colleagues, friends, etc.)

STATE OF MIND: Avoidance, anxiety, waiting period; or blindly brave, refused to protect and home observation.

5. People who don't want to see a doctor in public

Mentality: fear of being misdiagnosed and isolated, lack of awareness, avoidance, neglect, anxiety and so on.

6. Susceptible groups and the general public

State of mind: panic, dare not go out, blind disinfection, disappointment, fear, irritability, aggressive behavior and too optimistic, give up and so on.
